ce:section.ce:para:
According to the method described in Section 2.5, the GSH levels in two urine samples provided by volunteers were measured using fluorescence spectroscopy (IBlue/IYellow) and smartphone RGB method based on ratio fluorescence sensing platform. The results are presented in Table 1
                           . For two volunteers, GSH levels in their urine samples were 1718 and 1598 nmol/L (By IBlue/IYellow), 1695 and 1623 nmol/L (By RGB), respectively. According to the inference drawn from the logic gate, both samples should exhibit blue fluorescence. The experimental results show that this is indeed the case, and the blue fluorescence deepens after adding the standard solution. The detection results are almost the same as those of the general HPLC method (1720, 1610 nmol/L) (the HPLC chromatograms and standard curve are shown in Fig. S11 and S12). To verify detection accuracy, spiking experiments were conducted, revealing recovery rates within the range of 94.00–101.60 % for fluorescence spectroscopy and smartphone RGB methods. This confirms the accuracy and reliability of GSH detection results obtained from our constructed fluorescence sensing platform. Compared with other literature works (Table 2
                           ), our ratio fluorescence sensor exhibits higher sensitivity a broader linear range for GSH detection.
